filters/network/local_ratelimit/) and listener (source/extensions/filters/listener/local_ratelimit/) levels, allowing rate limiting to be applied before HTTP processing or even before TLS handshake, using the same token bucket implementation pattern.\n\n### Kubernetes Rate Limiting Architecture\n\n**1. Token Bucket Rate Limiter (Client-Side)**\nKubernetes client-go library implements a token bucket rate limiter in staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/util/flowcontrol/throttle.go. The NewTokenBucketRateLimiter function wraps the golang.org/x/time/rate.Limiter to provide a rate limiter that allows burst traffic while maintaining a smooth QPS. The tokenBucketRateLimiter struct wraps rate.Limiter and adds clock support for testability.\n\n**2. API Priority and Fairness (APF) Controller**\nThe Kubernetes API server implements sophisticated priority and fairness handling through the APF controller in staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_controller.go. The configController class watches FlowSchema and PriorityLevelConfiguration objects from the flowcontrol API group. The controller manages priorityLevelState objects for each priority level, implementing dynamic borrowing of concurrency capacity between priority levels through the updateBorrowing method called periodically every 10 seconds.\n\n**3. Fair Queuing Implementation**\nThe core queueing logic is implemented in staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/fairqueuing/queueset/, implementing the fair queuing for server requests technique. The queueSet class maintains separate queues for each flow schema, tracking virtual finish times and seats (concurrency units) using virtual clock calculations. This ensures fair resource allocation across different priority levels and flow schemas.\n\n**4. Priority Level Configuration**\nPriority levels are defined in staging/src/k8s.io/api/flowcontrol/v1/types.go and related versioned API types. Each PriorityLevelConfiguration specifies whether requests are exempt from limits (PriorityLevelEnablementExempt) or subject to concurrency limits (PriorityLevelEnablementLimited), with nominalConcurrencyShares controlling the fair share allocation.\n\n**5. APF Filter**\nThe apf_filter.go implements the HTTP filter that integrates APF with the HTTP request handling pipeline. The filter classifies incoming requests based on FlowSchema rules, dispatching them to the appropriate priority level queue, and ensuring proper waiting and execution handling.\n\n### Key Differences in Patterns\n\n**Envoy's approach:**\n- Uses token bucket as the primary mechanism at all levels\n- Supports distributed rate limiting via gRPC streaming to a centralized service\n- Separates local (per-connection/process) and global (distributed) rate limiting\n- Token buckets are configurable with fill intervals and tokens per fill\n\n**Kubernetes' approach:**\n- Combines token bucket with sophisticated fair queuing for multi-tenant scenarios\n- Implements priority-based scheduling with dynamic capacity borrowing\n- Tracks per-request work estimates and concurrency consumption\n- Uses virtual clock calculations for fair allocation of limited concurrency\n"
